{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473603","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473603"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:11:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2574"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2574"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.24,0.5,0.22,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101499"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2574"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2574"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83938"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1083"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"},{"type":"tags","id":"6219"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3862"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11509"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33999"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44082"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101499","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101499"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old girl is brought to the General Practice clinic by her parent due to pain in multiple joints for the past four months. She initially had pain in her knees, but for the past month has also experienced pain in her ankles, wrists, and elbows. The pain is worse in the morning and improves as the day progresses. She was born at term, has no significant medical history, does not take any regular medications, and is up to date with immunisations. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse is 78/min and temperature is 37\u00b0C. There is mild swelling and tenderness without erythema in her ankles, knees, elbows, and wrists. She is able to walk and has full range of motion in all joints. There is no rash or lymphadenopathy, and the remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management whilst awaiting rheumatology review?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Methotrexate","Physical therapy","Naproxen","Prednisolone","Etanercept"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with pain and swelling in more than four joints for over six weeks, with morning stiffness and improvement throughout the day, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Epolyarticular juvenile idiopathic arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E. The absence of fever, rash, or lymphadenopathy makes systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENaproxen\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug, is the most appropriate initial management to control pain and inflammation while awaiting specialist assessment. Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs are effective for symptom relief and are safe to initiate in primary care for suspected juvenile idiopathic arthritis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPhysical therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is important for long-term management to maintain joint function and prevent disability, but it is not the first step before pain and inflammation are controlled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is a disease-modifying antirheumatic drug used for persistent or severe juvenile idiopathic arthritis, but it is not started until after specialist review and confirmation of diagnosis due to the need for monitoring and potential adverse effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for severe or refractory cases, or when there are systemic features, due to its side effect profile. It is not recommended as initial therapy in uncomplicated cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEtanercept\u003C/strong\u003E is a biologic agent used for juvenile idiopathic arthritis unresponsive to first-line therapies, but it is not appropriate as initial management and requires specialist initiation and monitoring.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs are the first-line treatment for juvenile idiopathic arthritis while awaiting specialist review.","Juvenile idiopathic arthritis is classified by the number of joints involved and the presence or absence of systemic features.","Systemic juvenile idiopathic arthritis presents with fever and extra-articular features, distinguishing it from other subtypes."],"references":["Juvenile idiopathic arthritis. In: eTG complete [online]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2021. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Kliegman RM, Geme JWS. Nelson Textbook of Pediatrics: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Diagnosis and management of juvenile idiopathic arthritis [Internet]. [cited 2024 May 6]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/FSDEDEV/media/documents/Clinical%20Resources/Guidelines/Joint%20replacement/Algorithm-for-the-diagnosis-and-management-of-juvenile-idiopathic-arthritis.pdf","Ringold S, Angeles-Han ST, Beukelman T, Lovell D, Cuello CA, Becker ML, et al. 2019 American College of Rheumatology/Arthritis Foundation Guideline for the Treatment of Juvenile Idiopathic Arthritis: Therapeutic Approaches for Non-Systemic Polyarthritis, Sacroiliitis, and Enthesitis. Arthritis Care \u0026 Research [Internet]. 2019 April [cited 2024 June 1]. Available from: https://acrjournals.onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1002/acr.23870","Juvenile idiopathic arthritis (JIA), management in children [Internet]. [cited 6 may 2024]. Available from: https://www.clinicalguidelines.scot.nhs.uk/nhsggc-guidelines/nhsggc-guidelines/emergency-medicine/juvenile-idiopathic-arthritis-jia-management-in-children/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83938"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2574"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83938","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83938"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T11:19:16+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T11:20:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2574"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101499"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags"